The Finite Element Method (FEM) is an approach to solving problems involving partial differential equations. It is a numerical method that divides the problem into small regions and solves each region using a set of equations. The method was developed in the early 1900s by the German engineer L. Nusselt, who used it to solve problems in heat transfer. The method was further developed by mathematicians and engineers in the early 1960s, and it has since become a widely used tool in engineering, applied mathematics, and other fields.

The Finite Element Method (FEM) is used in engineering to model physical systems that can be divided into small elements. These elements are approximated using mathematical models. The FEM is an iterative process that solves for the unknowns in the system using linear algebra and numerical integration. The FEM can be used to solve problems in structural engineering, fluid dynamics, solid mechanics, heat transfer, and many other fields.

The Finite Element Method (FEM) has several advantages over other numerical methods:

It is well-suited for problems with complex geometries: FEM can model complex geometries, such as curved surfaces or irregular shapes, better than other numerical methods.
It is robust: FEM is robust against mesh dependence, making it suitable for large-scale simulations.
It is scalable: FEM can be scaled up or down to accommodate changes in the problem size or complexity.
It can handle nonlinearities: FEM can handle nonlinearity by using nonlinear elements or by using nonlinear elements in combination with linear elements.
It provides a good approximation: FEM provides a good approximation to the solution of the underlying PDEs.
It provides insight into the underlying physics: FEM provides insight into the underlying physics of the problem through its ability to capture complex phenomena such as heat conduction, fluid flow, or electromagnetics.
It is easy to implement: FEM can be implemented easily in a wide range of programming languages and computational environments.
